 21 Examples 21.1 Example 1: Capital Accumulation (Euler Method) Economic Context: In the Solow-style model, capital grows through investment and shrinks through depreciation: \[ rac{dK}{dt} = sK^\alpha - \delta K\] At steady state: \(K^* = \left( rac{s}{\delta}ight)^{1/(1-\alpha)}\). s &lt;- 0.3 delta &lt;- 0.05 alpha &lt;- 0.4 dt &lt;- 0.01 T &lt;- 500 K_low &lt;- numeric(T) K_high &lt;- numeric(T) K_low[1] &lt;- 2 K_high[1] &lt;- 50 for (t in 1:(T - 1)) { K_low[t+1] &lt;- K_low[t] + dt * (s * K_low[t]^alpha - delta * K_low[t]) K_high[t+1] &lt;- K_high[t] + dt * (s * K_high[t]^alpha - delta * K_high[t]) } K_star &lt;- (s / delta)^(1 / (1 - alpha)) cat(&quot;Analytical K* =&quot;, round(K_star, 3), &quot;
&quot;) ## Analytical K* = 19.812 cat(&quot;K_low at T =&quot;, round(K_low[T], 3), &quot;
&quot;) ## K_low at T = 3.551 cat(&quot;K_high at T =&quot;, round(K_high[T], 3), &quot;
&quot;) ## K_high at T = 45.159 df &lt;- data.frame( t = rep(1:T, 2), K = c(K_low, K_high), start = rep(c(&quot;K0 = 2&quot;, &quot;K0 = 50&quot;), each = T) ) ggplot(df, aes(x = t, y = K, color = start)) + geom_line(size = 1) + geom_hline(yintercept = K_star, linetype = &quot;dashed&quot;) + annotate(&quot;text&quot;, x = 400, y = K_star + 1.5, label = paste0(&quot;K* = &quot;, round(K_star, 2))) + labs(title = &quot;Capital Accumulation — Euler Method&quot;, x = &quot;Time Step&quot;, y = &quot;Capital K&quot;, color = &quot;Initial K&quot;) + theme_minimal() Interpretation: Both paths converge to \(K^*\) regardless of starting point, demonstrating the global stability of the steady state. 21.2 Example 2: Price Adjustment Dynamics (Euler Method) Economic Context: Prices adjust toward equilibrium \(P^*\) at speed \(\lambda\): \[ rac{dP}{dt} = \lambda(P^* - P), \quad P(0) = 60\] lambda &lt;- 0.3 P_star &lt;- 100 P0 &lt;- 60 dt &lt;- 0.1 T &lt;- 200 P &lt;- numeric(T) P[1] &lt;- P0 for (t in 1:(T - 1)) { P[t+1] &lt;- P[t] + dt * lambda * (P_star - P[t]) } ggplot(data.frame(t = 1:T, P = P), aes(x = t, y = P)) + geom_line(color = &quot;steelblue&quot;, size = 1) + geom_hline(yintercept = P_star, linetype = &quot;dashed&quot;, color = &quot;darkred&quot;) + annotate(&quot;text&quot;, x = 160, y = P_star - 3, label = &quot;P* = 100&quot;, color = &quot;darkred&quot;) + labs(title = &quot;Price Adjustment — Euler Method&quot;, x = &quot;Time Step&quot;, y = &quot;Price P(t)&quot;) + theme_minimal() 21.3 Example 3: Consumer Surplus (Integral Calculus) Economic Context: Consumer surplus is the area between the demand curve and the market price: \[CS = \int_0^{Q^*} \left[D(Q) - P^*ight] dQ\] a &lt;- 10; b &lt;- 0.5; P_star_cs &lt;- 4 Q_star &lt;- (a - P_star_cs) / b CS &lt;- 0.5 * (a - P_star_cs) * Q_star cat(&quot;Q* =&quot;, Q_star, &quot;
&quot;) ## Q* = 12 cat(&quot;Consumer Surplus (analytical) =&quot;, CS, &quot;
&quot;) ## Consumer Surplus (analytical) = 36 CS_num &lt;- integrate(function(Q) (a - b * Q) - P_star_cs, 0, Q_star)$value cat(&quot;Consumer Surplus (numerical) =&quot;, round(CS_num, 4), &quot;
